{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:38:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:38:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.21,0.11,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71388"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56867"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7051"},{"type":"tags","id":"7052"},{"type":"tags","id":"10570"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20332"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71388"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a paired structure in the male reproductive system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bulbourethral gland","Corpus spongiosum","Prostatic utricle","Penile urethra","Verumontanum"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomy of paired and unpaired structures in the male reproductive system is crucial for clinical practice. Most structures in the male reproductive tract exist as bilateral pairs, providing redundancy and maintaining fertility even if one side is damaged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBulbourethral glands\u003C/strong\u003E (also called Cowper\u0027s glands) are paired structures located below the prostate gland that secrete a clear fluid secondary to sexual arousal. This fluid helps neutralise urethral acidity and provides lubrication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus spongiosum\u003C/strong\u003E is an unpaired midline structure of erectile tissue that surrounds the penile urethra. It extends from the bulb of the penis to the glans penis and helps prevent the urethra from being compressed during erection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostatic utricle\u003C/strong\u003E is an unpaired midline blind-ending pouch in the posterior urethra, representing a remnant of the paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epenile urethra\u003C/strong\u003E is an unpaired midline tubular structure that extends from the bladder to the external urethral meatus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Everumontanum\u003C/strong\u003E (or seminal colliculus) is an unpaired midline elevation in the prostatic urethra where the ejaculatory ducts enter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important paired structures in the male reproductive system include the testes, epididymides, vas deferens, and seminal vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The corpus spongiosum is an unpaired midline structure of the penis containing the urethra.","Most male reproductive organs are paired structures including the testes, epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles, and bulbourethral glands.","Paired structures in the male reproductive system provide redundancy and maintain fertility even if one side is damaged."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Foster RA. Male Genital System. Jubb, Kennedy \u0026 Palmer\u0027s Pathology of Domestic Animals: Volume 3. 2016:465\u2013510.e1. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-7020-5319-1.00016-5. Epub 2016 Mar 18. PMCID: PMC7271154.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56867"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56867"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T11:44:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T11:45:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{